title: For Sale:  Saiga-12 Done Right
postcontent:
If you are one of the many who have been holding out for one, it won't get any better than this. Cash or USPS/ Western money order only. Buyer pays all FFL costs. Detailed pictures of internals/ externals provided for serious shoppers. 

This gun is one of two I bought a few months ago. Shoots both 2 3/4" and 3". Have put <250 rds through it; just enough to set it perfectly and properly break it in. If you know anything about these, you know that the magazines usually need to be significantly filed to fit each well, and that ejection problems are a given until they are properly calibrated. All of which is a big pain and makes each new gun something of a project. This one was taken right from the factory and set up by a friend/ Kalashnikov expert from Russia. Result: the mags fit perfectly, and the shells go right where they should. It runs like a clock. 

Barrel is in great condition. Used gently, still looks great outside. Has some minor scratches from wear. This one is ready to use, right out of the box. Just add an optic and go have a blast. These are of varying quality; this is one of the good ones. Made by Izhmash in Mother Russia and upgraded properly here in the USA. Will shoot hydrashock, sabot; you name it. Set up for slug, as it should be.

Great deal on a preban gun; no more will be imported. Awesome looking, solid, and accurate weapon that was configured for reliability, rather than as a range toy. Every time I shoot this it gets a lot of interest.

title: For Sale:  Marlin MR-7 .30-06
postcontent:
This rifle is in very good condition, with only a few tiny blemishes on the stock. I've only fired about 10 rounds through it, and it is very accurate. It comes with the high quality leather sling pictured.

This rifle has a 22" barrel with 6 groove precision rifling and a recessed muzzle. It has a heat treated receiver and extra strong bolt lock up, and features a 3-position safety, and a bolt face wrapped in 3 layers of 4140 steel, a highly visible cocking indicator and a shrouded striker. It also has an adjustable 3-6 lb. trigger, and a hinged floorplate with a removable 4 shot box magazine. It has a classic cut checkered American walnut stock.

This rifle was only produced during 1996-1999. This one was produced in 1997. These rifles can be hard to find these days. Rumor has it production ceased because it infringed on patents for the Model 700. It borrows several features from several popular rifles. The bolt design was taken from the Remington Model 700, the wing style safety is from the Winchester Model 70, the "dogleg" bolt handle is from the Ruger Model 77, and the detachable mag on the floor plate is from the Browning A-Bolt.

The EB-X reticle has a fine crosshair with four heavy posts and three holdover subtension marks that provide secondary aiming points compatible with the ballistics of most moderate caliber hunting rifles. This refined model of the Grand Slam series includes features that offer improved handling and functionality compared to previous Grand Slam riflescope versions. As the flagship series of Weaver's riflescope line, the Grand Slam delivers fully multicoated optics and shockproof construction at a reasonable price.

Weaver's proprietary Micro-Trac windage and elevation adjustment system has been improved to deliver more consistent performance and precise 1/4 MOA aiming point correction. Two springs on each correction axis deliver enhanced durability, and improve the scope's ability to maintain zero even when used on heavy caliber firearms. Curved grooves on the scope's turret caps and ocular focus dial are designed to provide sleek aesthetics, as well as tactile feedback when wearing gloves.

This configuration of the Grand Slam series features a 4-16x magnification range that is well-suited for most shooting distances at the target range or on the hunt. For improved accuracy at the higher end of the magnification range, this riflescope includes a parallax adjustment knob for setting the target distance beyond a 40-yard (36m) range.

Complementing the durability and functionality of the 4-16x Grand Slam is a 44mm objective lens and fully multicoated optical path that transmit sufficient light to help a shooter acquire their target during the final hour of daylight. The incomparable Sig Sauer P226 has a TacOps version, which includes the Short Reset Trigger, SigLite night sights (front sight is also fiber optic and tritium) and FOUR extended mags (15+1 in .40).  I have put through about 150 rounds and have had this as my nightstand gun. Also, this is a FOR SALE ONLY; I am not interested in a trade, so please don't ask!  (I am about 100% sure that some knucklehead WILL still make a lowball offer or ask about a trade!) :-)

NOTE:  I HAVE IT LISTED ELSEWHERE, AND IT MIGHT SELL THERE FAIRLY SOON.  

Without the Streamlight laser/flashlight: $825 with the light $900.

FAQ'S:

Does the gun come with box and all papers?   Yes
How many mags? FOUR extended mags, 15+1
Will you consider a trade?  NO
What is your best price?  The prices listed
When can I get the gun?  After all Illinois laws are followed for in-state transfer. 72 hours, etc.

up for sale is my lightly used EOTECH EXPS 3-4 + G33 magnifier package (latest generation). For those that need info on the HHS 1 package a simple google search will pull up all the details.

Why settle for a BDC reticle that is caliber, rifle and ammo specific when you can put this eotech on and off ANY rifle, ANY system and have the exact values of each dot? Hunters can value from this very much as semi auto hunting is gaining popularity, especially with a 308 caliber.

Don't buy new when you can buy this used pristine excellent condition EOTECH package.

title: For Sale:  Toyo Kogyo Arisaka Type 99, Series 35, in-tact 'mum, matching, last ditch
postcontent:
This is a Japanese WW2 rifle made during their last ditch efforts to win the war. Late series rifles made during this time are thus called "last ditch" and feature somewhat crude construction compared to rifles made earlier. This makes it an interesting collectors piece. It is chambered in 7.7x58mm.

It still has its Chrysanthemum intact, which is somewhat rare and implies the rifle was captured in the field as opposed to being turned over at the end of the war. Most of these rifles had their 'mum ground off completely to preserve the Japanese emperors honor. It has plain iron sights with no anti-aircraft calipers like earlier rifles did. It does not have any of the typical Arisaka accessories such as the bayonet, monopod or dust cover. 

The serial number on the striker matches the one on the receiver, however there is no serial number at all on the bolt body, safety knob, or bayonet lug. This is typical of a last ditch Arisaka. Being a war souvenir captured in the field, it does not have any import marks. There is a bit of rust on the receiver and barrel, partly because the metal on last ditch rifles was not given as nice a finish, but it could easily be cleaned up. The striker mechanism is still in great condition and it seems to dry fire perfectly.
